#!/usr/bin/env python3
"""kb-zoom-extract — carve recent Zoom transcripts from the "My Notes" cache.

WHY THIS EXISTS / HOW IT WORKS (read before editing):

- Zoom stopped writing local ``meeting_saved_closed_caption.txt`` files. The only
  fresh source of transcripts is Zoom's "My Notes" WebKit IndexedDB SQLite cache
  under ``~/Library/Application Support/zoom.us/data/UnifyWebView_Cache``.

- TRANSCRIPT LIFECYCLE (why we carve freed pages, not query live rows): while a
  meeting's "My Notes" panel is open, Zoom writes each utterance as a LIVE SQL
  row in the ``notes:transcript:v1`` object store of the ``Records`` table. Once
  Zoom syncs the notes to the cloud it DELETES those rows. The deleted rows then
  survive in SQLite freelist (freed) pages for ~2-3 days before the pages are
  recycled and overwritten. We therefore CARVE the raw file bytes by pattern: a
  live SQL query catches only meetings whose panel is still open, but byte-
  carving the freelist also recovers the recently-deleted ones. Run on a frequent
  cadence (every 15 min) the freed pages always outlive the interval, so nothing
  is missed. (Meeting metadata lives in the ``file:node:v1`` store, not
  ``notes:meetings:v1``, which is empty.)

- THE WAL HOLDS THE FRESHEST DATA: the primary ``IndexedDB.sqlite3`` has a
  ``IndexedDB.sqlite3-wal`` sidecar that buffers recent writes before checkpoint.
  Freshly clicked / live transcript rows land in the WAL first and may dwarf the
  checkpointed main DB. We therefore read BOTH the main DB and (if present and
  non-empty) the ``-wal`` sidecar, copying main-then-wal for a consistent
  snapshot, and carve EACH buffer SEPARATELY (never concatenated — a clone record
  could straddle the join). Carving is pure byte-pattern matching, so the WAL's
  frame headers are irrelevant: the clone-serialized records in page payloads are
  recovered directly from the raw WAL bytes.

- BACKFILL / PAGE RECYCLING (``--watch``): clicking a meeting in My Notes pulls
  its transcript from the cloud into the cache, but opening the NEXT meeting
  reuses the freed pages that held the previous one's just-deleted rows. A single
  carve after a click-through catches only the last 2-3 meetings. ``--watch``
  defeats this by polling on an interval and accumulating a UNION of everything
  ever seen across polls into persistent ``meetings``/``utts`` accumulators, so a
  meeting captured in poll N survives even after its pages are recycled in poll
  N+1. In watch mode (and ONLY there) caption files we own may be REWRITTEN when
  the accumulated transcript grows; the scheduled single-shot run never rewrites.

- The stored values are WebKit CloneSerialization, NOT V8. Field names are plain
  ASCII and string values are Latin1, so stdlib byte-scanning decodes them — no
  V8 deserializer and no third-party deps (sqlite3 is unused because carving the
  freelist reaches deleted rows that SQL cannot). Each utterance object carries:
  ``messageId``, ``message``, ``timeStampContent`` (HH:MM:SS wall clock),
  ``startTimeMsec`` (epoch-ms), ``username``, plus fields we ignore. Meeting
  metadata records carry an ``i`` (id) and ``n`` (title); the title embeds
  ``<Title> YYYY-MM-DD HH:MM(GMT...)``.

- Utterances carry no note-id, so they are associated to a meeting by TIME: each
  utterance's ``startTimeMsec`` is bucketed to the nearest preceding meeting
  start. The host timezone is assumed to match the meeting's (verified: the
  embedded GMT offset matched the machine local time).

- Freed pages hold MANY stale copies of the same utterance; dedup by
  ``messageId`` collapses them, and we sort by ``startTimeMsec`` for strict
  chronological order (``timeStampContent`` lacks a date, so it would mis-sort a
  meeting crossing midnight).

IDEMPOTENCY: a sibling ``.kb-zoom-extract`` sentinel is written next to every
caption file this tool creates. A Zoom-authored caption (no sentinel) is NEVER
overwritten, in any mode (``present-foreign -> skip``); ``absent -> write +
sentinel``. For a caption WE own (``present-ours``) the rule is grow-if-bigger,
never shrink — and the two modes get their baseline from different places:

- Single-shot (scheduled): the on-disk caption IS the baseline. We count the
  utterances already in our file and REWRITE only when the fresh carve is
  strictly larger, otherwise skip. This lets a later, fuller poll supersede an
  earlier partial mid-meeting carve, while a thin freelist carve can never shrink
  the big cloud-backfilled captions already on disk (which always dwarf it).
- ``--watch`` (backfill): the data source is a growing in-memory UNION across
  polls, so the baseline is what we last wrote THIS process (first-poll baseline
  0); a caption we own is rewritten only when that union is strictly larger.

Either way a file only ever grows, and a foreign/real Zoom caption is never
touched. The sentinel records provenance so a human can tell synthetic captions
from real Zoom ones.

Usage:
  kb-zoom-extract [--since YYYY-MM-DD | --days N] [--zoom-dir DIR]
                  [--cache-glob GLOB] [--dry-run] [--watch [INTERVAL]]

  Single-shot (default, and what the scheduled LaunchAgent runs): carve once,
  write any new in-window caption files and GROW our own existing ones when the
  fresh carve is strictly larger (never shrink, never touch real Zoom captions).
  WAL-aware, so it surfaces more than before.

  Backfill (operator-driven, manual): to pull a batch of older meetings out of
  the cloud into local captions, run:

      kb-zoom-extract --watch --since YYYY-MM-DD

  then open Zoom's "My Notes" panel and click each meeting ONE AT A TIME. After
  each click, wait for the ``captured: <dir> (<n> utterances)`` line to print
  before moving to the next meeting (that line confirms the just-clicked
  transcript landed in the accumulated union). The union grows across polls, so
  a meeting stays captured even after its cache pages are recycled by the next
  click. Press Ctrl-C when done; a final summary of everything captured prints.
  ``--watch`` polls every 15s by default; ``--watch 20`` polls every 20s.

Exit codes: 0 on success AND on benign no-ops (Zoom closed / cache missing /
nothing in window) and on Ctrl-C out of ``--watch``. Non-zero only on a hard
failure (a located DB unreadable in single-shot mode).
"""

import argparse
import datetime
import glob
import os
import re
import shutil
import struct
import sys
import tempfile
import time

# WebKit clone tags we care about.
_STR_TAG = 0x10  # Latin1/UTF-16 string value
_DBL_TAG = 0x0A  # IEEE-754 double value (\n)

# Meeting record anchor: object-start + key "i" + string tag.
_MEETING_ANCHOR = b"\x0f\x00\x00\x00\x02\x01\x00\x00\x80i\x10"

_TITLE_RE = re.compile(
    r"^(?P<name>.*?)\s+(?P<d>\d{4}-\d{2}-\d{2})\s+(?P<h>\d{2}):(?P<m>\d{2})\(GMT"
)


def _key_marker(name):
    """The on-disk bytes that introduce object key ``name`` (length|Latin1 flag)."""
    return struct.pack("<I", len(name) | 0x80000000) + name.encode("latin1")


def decode_clone_string(buf, pos):
    """Decode a WebKit clone string value at ``pos``.

    Returns ``(text, new_pos)`` or ``(None, pos)`` if there is no string tag.
    The length word's high bit (0x80000000) marks a Latin1 (8-bit) string;
    otherwise it is UTF-16LE.
    """
    if pos < 0 or pos + 5 > len(buf) or buf[pos] != _STR_TAG:
        return None, pos
    word = struct.unpack_from("<I", buf, pos + 1)[0]
    pos += 5
    length = word & 0x7FFFFFFF
    if word & 0x80000000:
        end = pos + length
        return buf[pos:end].decode("latin1", "replace"), end
    end = pos + length * 2
    return buf[pos:end].decode("utf-16-le", "replace"), end


def _find_string_field(record, key):
    """Find key ``key`` inside ``record`` and decode its string value, or None."""
    anchor = _key_marker(key) + bytes([_STR_TAG])
    i = record.find(anchor)
    if i < 0:
        return None
    # decode_clone_string expects to start at the string tag itself.
    s, _ = decode_clone_string(record, i + len(anchor) - 1)
    return s


def _find_double_field(record, key):
    anchor = _key_marker(key) + bytes([_DBL_TAG])
    i = record.find(anchor)
    if i < 0 or i + len(anchor) + 8 > len(record):
        return None
    return struct.unpack_from("<d", record, i + len(anchor))[0]


def parse_title(title):
    """Split a meeting title into ``(clean_title, start_datetime)`` or None.

    Meeting titles are stored as ``"<Title> YYYY-MM-DD HH:MM(GMT...)"``. Records
    without that suffix (e.g. "My notes", a person's name) are not meetings.
    """
    m = _TITLE_RE.match(title)
    if not m:
        return None
    name = m.group("name").strip()
    if not name:
        return None
    dt = datetime.datetime.strptime(
        f"{m.group('d')} {m.group('h')}:{m.group('m')}", "%Y-%m-%d %H:%M"
    )
    return name, dt


def carve_meetings(data):
    """Carve meeting metadata from raw bytes -> ``{meeting_id: title}`` (deduped)."""
    out = {}
    for m in re.finditer(re.escape(_MEETING_ANCHOR), data):
        pos = m.end() - 1  # back up to the string tag of the "i" value
        mid, pos = decode_clone_string(data, pos)
        if not mid:
            continue
        # The next key should be "n" (title).
        nkey = _key_marker("n")
        if data[pos : pos + len(nkey)] != nkey:
            continue
        title, _ = decode_clone_string(data, pos + len(nkey))
        if title:
            out[mid] = title
    return out


def carve_utterances(data):
    """Carve transcript utterances -> ``{messageId: {...}}`` (deduped by id).

    Records are sliced between consecutive ``messageId`` anchors; ``messageId``
    is the first field of each utterance object, so each slice holds exactly one
    record's fields. The last record is bounded by an 8 KiB cap.
    """
    anchor = _key_marker("messageId") + bytes([_STR_TAG])
    starts = [m.start() for m in re.finditer(re.escape(anchor), data)]
    out = {}
    for idx, start in enumerate(starts):
        end = starts[idx + 1] if idx + 1 < len(starts) else min(start + 8192, len(data))
        record = data[start:end]
        mid, _ = decode_clone_string(record, len(anchor) - 1)
        if not mid:
            continue
        ts = _find_string_field(record, "timeStampContent")
        if not ts:
            continue
        out[mid] = {
            "ts": ts,
            "message": _find_string_field(record, "message") or "",
            "username": _find_string_field(record, "username") or "Unknown",
            "start_ms": _find_double_field(record, "startTimeMsec"),
        }
    return out


def bucket_utterances(utts, meetings, slack_seconds=300):
    """Group utterances under the nearest preceding meeting start.

    ``meetings`` is a list of ``(start_datetime, clean_title, meeting_id)``.
    An utterance joins the latest meeting whose start (minus ``slack_seconds``,
    to tolerate captions that begin a touch before the scheduled time) is at or
    before the utterance's ``startTimeMsec``. Utterances with no usable timestamp
    or no preceding meeting are dropped.
    """
    ordered = sorted(meetings, key=lambda t: t[0])
    buckets = {}
    for u in utts.values():
        if not u.get("start_ms"):
            continue
        when = u["start_ms"] / 1000.0
        chosen = None
        for meeting in ordered:
            if meeting[0].timestamp() - slack_seconds <= when:
                chosen = meeting
            else:
                break
        if chosen is not None:
            buckets.setdefault(chosen, []).append(u)
    return buckets


def render_caption(utterances):
    """Render utterances into the kb-distill chunker caption format, sorted
    chronologically by ``startTimeMsec``."""
    lines = []
    for u in sorted(utterances, key=lambda x: (x.get("start_ms") or 0, x["ts"])):
        msg = (u.get("message") or "").strip()
        lines.append(f"[{u['username']} {u['ts']}]\n{msg}\n")
    return "\n".join(lines)


def dir_name(dt, title):
    """Build the ``YYYY-MM-DD HH.MM.SS <Title>`` dir name Zoom would use.

    Start time is known only to the minute, so seconds are ``00``. Zoom replaces
    ``/`` with ``_`` in titles (e.g. "Andrew / Joe" -> "Andrew _ Joe")."""
    safe = title.replace("/", "_")
    return f"{dt.strftime('%Y-%m-%d %H.%M')}.00 {safe}"


_SENTINEL = ".kb-zoom-extract"

# One utterance == one speaker-block header line. This is the same regex the
# kb-distill chunker uses to split a caption into utterances: a bracketed header
# carrying an HH:MM:SS wall-clock time (e.g. ``[Alice 13:58:00]``). Counting these
# in an on-disk caption tells us how many utterances it currently holds, which is
# the baseline the single-shot grow-if-bigger path compares a fresh carve against.
_HEADER_RE = re.compile(r"^\[[^]]*[0-9][0-9]:[0-9][0-9]:[0-9][0-9][^]]*\]", re.MULTILINE)


def _count_caption_utterances(path):
    """Count utterances in an existing caption file on disk (header lines).

    Returns the number of speaker-block headers (one per utterance). A missing or
    unreadable file counts as 0, so the caller treats it as "grow from nothing".
    """
    try:
        with open(path, encoding="utf-8") as fh:
            text = fh.read()
    except OSError:
        return 0
    return len(_HEADER_RE.findall(text))


def emit(meetings, utts, zoom_dir, cutoff, dry_run=False, allow_grow=False,
         written_counts=None, grow_from_disk=False):
    """Write caption files for in-window meetings. Returns ``(written, skipped)``.

    ``written`` entries are ``(dir_name, count)``; a third element ``"grew"`` is
    appended when an existing caption WE own was rewritten larger (vs a fresh
    write, which has no third element). ``skipped`` entries are
    ``(dir_name, reason)`` where reason is "exists-ours" or "exists-foreign".
    ``cutoff`` is a ``date``; meetings whose start date is before it are ignored.

    Two independent grow paths, never combined:

    - ``allow_grow`` (watch mode only) permits REWRITING a caption file we own
      when the freshly accumulated in-memory union is strictly larger than what
      we last wrote THIS process; ``written_counts`` is the mutable
      ``{dir_name: count}`` state tracking that (first-poll baseline 0).
    - ``grow_from_disk`` (single-shot only) has no cross-invocation memory, so
      the on-disk caption IS the baseline: it counts the utterances already in
      our existing caption and rewrites only when the fresh carve is STRICTLY
      larger, never shrinking it. This supersedes a partial mid-meeting carve
      with a later fuller one, while leaving the big cloud-backfilled captions
      (which dwarf any freelist carve) untouched.

    A foreign caption (no sentinel) is NEVER overwritten in any mode, preserving
    the never-clobber-a-real-Zoom-caption contract.
    """
    parsed = []
    for mid, title in meetings.items():
        pt = parse_title(title)
        if pt is None:
            continue
        name, dt = pt
        parsed.append((dt, name, mid))

    buckets = bucket_utterances(utts, parsed)
    written, skipped = [], []
    for (dt, name, _mid), lst in buckets.items():
        if dt.date() < cutoff:
            continue
        dname = dir_name(dt, name)
        ddir = os.path.join(zoom_dir, dname)
        cap = os.path.join(ddir, "meeting_saved_closed_caption.txt")
        n = len(lst)
        if os.path.exists(cap):
            ours = os.path.exists(os.path.join(ddir, _SENTINEL))
            if not ours:
                # A real Zoom caption — never clobber it, in any mode.
                skipped.append((dname, "exists-foreign"))
                continue
            if grow_from_disk:
                # Single-shot: the on-disk caption is the baseline (no in-memory
                # state survives between scheduled runs). Grow only if the fresh
                # carve has strictly more utterances than what is already there;
                # never shrink (protects rich cloud-backfilled captions).
                disk_count = _count_caption_utterances(cap)
                if n <= disk_count:
                    skipped.append((dname, "exists-ours"))
                    continue
                if not dry_run:
                    with open(cap, "w", encoding="utf-8") as fh:
                        fh.write(render_caption(lst))
                written.append((dname, n, "grew"))
                continue
            if not allow_grow:
                skipped.append((dname, "exists-ours"))
                continue
            # Watch mode: rewrite only if the accumulated union has grown.
            # First poll baseline is 0 (not the existing file's line count) so an
            # existing-ours caption is always refreshed from the fresh union.
            prev = written_counts.get(dname, 0)
            if n <= prev:
                skipped.append((dname, "exists-ours"))
                continue
            if not dry_run:
                with open(cap, "w", encoding="utf-8") as fh:
                    fh.write(render_caption(lst))
            written_counts[dname] = n
            written.append((dname, n))
            continue
        # No caption yet — write fresh.
        if dry_run:
            written.append((dname, n))
            if written_counts is not None:
                written_counts[dname] = n
            continue
        os.makedirs(ddir, exist_ok=True)
        with open(cap, "w", encoding="utf-8") as fh:
            fh.write(render_caption(lst))
        with open(os.path.join(ddir, _SENTINEL), "w", encoding="utf-8") as fh:
            fh.write("synthetic caption carved from Zoom My Notes IndexedDB cache\n")
        if written_counts is not None:
            written_counts[dname] = n
        written.append((dname, n))
    return written, skipped


# ---- cache location + driver ---------------------------------------------
_CACHE_GLOB = (
    "{home}/Library/Application Support/zoom.us/data/UnifyWebView_Cache/WebKit/"
    "UnSigned/Default/MyNotes/Origins/**/IndexedDB.sqlite3"
)


def _read_db_buffers(path):
    """Copy the (possibly Zoom-locked) DB and its WAL sidecar; return raw buffers.

    Returns a list of byte buffers: the main ``IndexedDB.sqlite3`` always, plus
    its ``IndexedDB.sqlite3-wal`` sidecar when present and non-empty. They are
    copied main-then-wal for a consistent snapshot and returned SEPARATELY (not
    concatenated) so a clone record cannot be lost straddling the join — each
    buffer is carved on its own by the caller.
    """
    fd, tmp = tempfile.mkstemp(prefix="kb-zoom-", suffix=".sqlite3")
    os.close(fd)
    fd_wal, tmp_wal = tempfile.mkstemp(prefix="kb-zoom-", suffix=".sqlite3-wal")
    os.close(fd_wal)
    wal_path = path + "-wal"
    try:
        shutil.copy2(path, tmp)  # main DB first
        have_wal = os.path.exists(wal_path) and os.path.getsize(wal_path) > 0
        if have_wal:
            shutil.copy2(wal_path, tmp_wal)
        buffers = []
        with open(tmp, "rb") as fh:
            buffers.append(fh.read())
        if have_wal:
            with open(tmp_wal, "rb") as fh:
                buffers.append(fh.read())
        return buffers
    finally:
        for t in (tmp, tmp_wal):
            try:
                os.remove(t)
            except OSError:
                pass


def _scan_into(dbs, meetings, utts):
    """Carve every located DB + WAL into the ``meetings``/``utts`` accumulators.

    Each buffer (main and WAL) is carved separately and merged; dedup keeps the
    first-seen record per id (``setdefault``). Raises ``OSError`` if a DB cannot
    be copied/read — the caller decides whether that is fatal.
    """
    for db in dbs:
        for data in _read_db_buffers(db):
            meetings.update(carve_meetings(data))
            for mid, u in carve_utterances(data).items():
                utts.setdefault(mid, u)


def _resolve_cutoff(args):
    if args.since:
        return datetime.datetime.strptime(args.since, "%Y-%m-%d").date()
    return datetime.date.today() - datetime.timedelta(days=args.days)


def _watch(dbs, args, cutoff, interval):
    """Backfill loop: poll the cache, accumulate a growing union, emit on growth.

    Persistent accumulators (``meetings``/``utts``/``written_counts``) are NEVER
    reset across iterations — that union is what defeats page recycling. Prints a
    ``captured:`` line only when a meeting is newly written or grown, so the
    operator can pace their click-through. Ctrl-C prints a final summary.
    """
    meetings, utts = {}, {}
    written_counts = {}
    print(f"kb-zoom-extract: watching {len(dbs)} cache DB(s) every {interval}s; "
          f"window since {cutoff.isoformat()}. Click each My Notes meeting, wait "
          f"for its 'captured:' line, then Ctrl-C when done.", file=sys.stderr)
    try:
        while True:
            try:
                _scan_into(dbs, meetings, utts)
            except OSError as exc:
                print(f"kb-zoom-extract: cache read failed this poll: {exc}", file=sys.stderr)
            written, _skipped = emit(
                meetings, utts, args.zoom_dir, cutoff,
                dry_run=args.dry_run, allow_grow=True, written_counts=written_counts,
            )
            verb = "would capture" if args.dry_run else "captured"
            for dname, n in written:
                print(f"{verb}: {dname} ({n} utterances)")
            time.sleep(interval)
    except KeyboardInterrupt:
        total_utts = sum(written_counts.values())
        print(file=sys.stderr)
        print(f"kb-zoom-extract: done. {len(written_counts)} meeting(s) / "
              f"{total_utts} utterance(s) captured; {len(utts)} utterances seen "
              f"in cache union.", file=sys.stderr)
        for dname in sorted(written_counts):
            print(f"  {dname} ({written_counts[dname]} utterances)", file=sys.stderr)
        if not written_counts:
            print("  (nothing captured)", file=sys.stderr)
        return 0


def main(argv=None):
    ap = argparse.ArgumentParser(description="Carve recent Zoom transcripts from My Notes cache.")
    grp = ap.add_mutually_exclusive_group()
    grp.add_argument("--since", help="only meetings on/after this YYYY-MM-DD")
    grp.add_argument("--days", type=int, default=7, help="lookback window in days (default 7)")
    ap.add_argument("--zoom-dir", default=os.path.expanduser("~/Documents/Zoom"))
    ap.add_argument("--cache-glob", default=_CACHE_GLOB.format(home=os.path.expanduser("~")))
    ap.add_argument("--dry-run", action="store_true")
    ap.add_argument(
        "--watch", nargs="?", const=15, type=int, metavar="INTERVAL",
        help="backfill mode: poll the cache every INTERVAL seconds (default 15) "
             "accumulating a growing union, rewriting our caption files as they "
             "grow; Ctrl-C to stop. Without this flag, runs once and grows our "
             "own captions if a larger carve is found (never shrinks, never "
             "overwrites a real Zoom caption).",
    )
    args = ap.parse_args(argv)

    cutoff = _resolve_cutoff(args)
    dbs = glob.glob(args.cache_glob, recursive=True)
    if not dbs:
        print("kb-zoom-extract: no My Notes cache found (Zoom never ran here?) — nothing to do", file=sys.stderr)
        return 0

    if args.watch is not None:
        return _watch(dbs, args, cutoff, args.watch)

    meetings, utts = {}, {}
    try:
        _scan_into(dbs, meetings, utts)
    except OSError as exc:
        print(f"kb-zoom-extract: cannot read cache DB: {exc}", file=sys.stderr)
        return 1

    if not utts:
        print(f"kb-zoom-extract: scanned {len(dbs)} cache DB(s), found no carvable "
              f"transcripts (cache may have been recycled) — nothing to do", file=sys.stderr)
        return 0

    written, skipped = emit(
        meetings, utts, args.zoom_dir, cutoff,
        dry_run=args.dry_run, grow_from_disk=True,
    )

    write_verb = "would write" if args.dry_run else "wrote"
    grow_verb = "would grow" if args.dry_run else "grew"
    print(f"kb-zoom-extract: {len(meetings)} meetings / {len(utts)} utterances in cache; "
          f"window since {cutoff.isoformat()}")
    for entry in written:
        dname, n = entry[0], entry[1]
        grew = len(entry) > 2 and entry[2] == "grew"
        verb = grow_verb if grew else write_verb
        print(f"  {verb}: {dname} ({n} utterances)")
    for dname, why in skipped:
        print(f"  skip ({why}): {dname}")
    if not written and not skipped:
        print("  (no meetings in window had carvable transcripts)")
    return 0


if __name__ == "__main__":
    raise SystemExit(main())
